The article discusses the significance of Juneteenth, a holiday that commemorates the emancipation of enslaved African Americans in the United States. It acknowledges the history of slavery as America's original sin and emphasizes the importance of reflecting on its terrible toll. The article also highlights the contributions made by enslaved individuals and their descendants to the nation's development. Last year, Juneteenth was declared a national holiday, providing an opportunity for reflection and a commitment to achieving racial justice and equity. The efforts of Congress, specifically Representative Al Green and Senator Elizabeth Warren, are recognized in acknowledging the significance of Juneteenth.